A ficus is a leafy, tropical tree or a houseplant with shiny leaves. Ficus is a genus of about 850 species of woody trees, shrubs, vines, epiphytes, bromeliads, and evergreen climbing plants in the family Moraceae. They are native throughout the tropics ( warmest biogeographic region on Earth ). Most ficus plants are indigenous to the wetter parts of the tropics and subtropics. Some species grow at high altitudes in the cooler mountains. These include f. chinensis ( sassafras ). In addition, species of ficus occur in arid climates, as well as in the shaded understorey of the tropical rainforest. The highest natural distribution is in eastern Australia. Ficus (/ˈfiːkəs/ ) means fig in Latin ficus /ˈfiːkəslatinit : figus, from fio, fiem, figere, meaning to beat or strike. Ficus is derived from the Greek word φίκος ( ficos ), for the plant. It does not mean fig in Latin, but the fig tree. The name is derived from the Ancient Greek language word φίκυς, fikus. In earlier usage its masculine singular and plural forms are listed as ficus and figurae.
